{"title_page": "Krusty Krab", "text_new": "{{pp-sock|small=yes}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|Fictional restaurant in SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n{{Infobox fictional business \n| name       = The Krusty Krab\n| image      = Krusty Krab 230b.png\n| image_size = 240px\n| caption    =\n| series     = ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''\n| first      = \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\" (1999)\n| type       = [[Fast food restaurant]]\n| owner      = [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene Krabs]]<!-- DO NOT add Viacom or other real-world companies as the owner.-->\n| founded    =\n| location   = [[Bikini Bottom]]\n| employees  = {{plainlist|\n* [[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob SquarePants]] ([[fry cook]])\n* [[Squidward Tentacles]] ([[cashier]])\n}}\n| products   = [[Krabby Patty|Krabby Patties]]\n| slogan    = \"Come Spend Your Money Here!\"<ref name=\"As Seen on TV\">{{cite episode|title=As Seen on TV|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=3|number=47a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=March 8, 2002|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Merriwether Williams|Williams, Merriwether]] (writers)}}</ref><!-- Slogan given in \"As Seen on TV\", so don't remove it. -->\n}}\n\nThe '''Krusty Krab''' is a fictional [[fast food restaurant]] in the American animated television series ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''. It is famous for its signature burger, the [[Krabby Patty]], the formula to which is a closely guarded [[trade secret]].\n\nThe restaurant was founded by [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene H. Krabs]] (Mr. Krabs), who is also the owner and manager. It has two full-time employees: [[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob SquarePants]], who works as the [[chef|fry cook]]; and [[Squidward Tentacles]], who works as the [[cashier]]. The Krusty Krab is deemed \"the finest eating establishment ever established for eating\" in [[Bikini Bottom]], and it is constantly challenged by its primary competitor, the [[Chum Bucket (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Chum Bucket]], which is operated by Mr. Krabs' [[archenemy|nemesis]] and former best friend, [[Plankton and Karen#Plankton|Plankton]].\n\nOne of the main settings of the series, the Krusty Krab was introduced in the pilot episode, \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\", where SpongeBob applies for the fry cook job at the restaurant. The Krusty Krab has also been featured in other media, including a [[SpongeBob SquarePants (film series)|theatrical film series]], a [[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|Broadway musical]], video games, and toys. The restaurant has been referenced or parodied throughout popular culture. It has also inspired real-life establishments.\n\n==Role in ''SpongeBob SquarePants''==\n[[File:Krusty Krab interior 50b.png|thumb|left|Inside the restaurant, Squidward is working the cash register, and various characters are eating Krabby Patties.]]\nThe Krusty Krab is a prominent fast food restaurant in the underwater city of [[Bikini Bottom]]. It is owned and operated by [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene H. Krabs]] (Mr. Krabs), who invented its famous Krabby Patty sandwich.<ref name=\"Friend or Foe\">{{cite episode|title=[[Friend or Foe (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Friend or Foe]]|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=5|number=81|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=April 13, 2007|credits=[[Casey Alexander (cartoonist)|Alexander, Casey]]; Cervas, Zeus; [[Mike Mitchell (director)|Mitchell, Mike]]; [[Steven Banks|Banks, Steven]]; [[Tim Hill (director)|Hill, Tim]] (writers)}}</ref> Mr. Krabs has two employees: [[Squidward Tentacles]] and [[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob SquarePants]], who work as the [[cashier]] and [[chef|fry cook]], respectively. [[Patrick Star]] has also worked at the Krusty Krab for several brief stints in a variety of positions.\n\nLocated across the street from the Krusty Krab is the Chum Bucket, another fast food restaurant owned and operated by [[Plankton and Karen]].<ref name=\"Friend or Foe\"/> Plankton, Mr. Krabs' former best friend,<ref name=\"Friend or Foe\"/> later became his arch-competitor;<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Algae's Always Greener|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=3|number=41a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=March 22, 2002|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Merriwether Williams|Williams, Merriwether]] (writers)}}</ref> Plankton's futile attempts at stealing the secret Krabby Patty recipe to replicate the burgers and put the Krusty Krab out of business is a major plot point throughout the series.\n\nThe Krusty Krab usually attracts customers from Bikini Bottom because of the Krabby Patty's renowned taste and the fact that Plankton's restaurant has a menu consisting of [[chumming|chum]] (bait consisting of fish parts), which is considered mostly inedible by the other characters.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Chum Bucket Supreme|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=6|number=122a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=July 19, 2009|credits=Charmatz, Sean; [[Dani Michaeli|Michaeli, Dani]] (writers)}}</ref> As a result, the Krusty Krab has become one of the most successful restaurants in the city.<ref name=\"Hist\"/> In the show, SpongeBob calls it \"the finest eating establishment ever established for eating\".<ref>{{cite episode|title=[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=1|number=1a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=May 1, 1999|credits=[[Stephen Hillenburg|Hillenburg, Stephen]]; [[Derek Drymon|Drymon, Derek]]; [[Tim Hill (director)|Hill, Tim]] (writers)}}</ref> Mr. Krabs frequently exploits his restaurant's popularity, such as engaging in [[price gouging]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Krusty Sponge|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=5|number=89a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=July 24, 2007|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; Shaw, Eric (writers)}}</ref> and charging his own employees for use of the building's services.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Squid on Strike|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=2|number=40a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=October 12, 2001|credits=[[Walt Dohrn|Dohrn, Walt]]; [[Paul Tibbitt|Tibbitt, Paul]]; [[Mark O'Hare|O'Hare, Mark]] (writers)}}</ref>\n\nIn one episode, the Krusty Krab building is shown to have originally been a run-down retirement home called the Rusty Krab, which Mr. Krabs acquired and converted into a restaurant.<ref name=\"Hist\">{{cite episode|title=Krusty Krab Training Video|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=3|number=50b|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=May 10, 2002|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Kent Osborne|Osborne, Kent]] (writers)}}</ref> In another episode, the restaurant was also the name of a pirate ship owned by Mr. Krabs before he started the business.<ref name=\"Grandpappy the Pirate\">{{cite episode|title=Grandpappy the Pirate|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=6|number=115a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=February 18, 2009|credits=[[Casey Alexander (cartoonist)|Alexander, Casey]]; Cervas, Zeus; [[Dani Michaeli|Michaeli, Dani]] (writers)}}</ref> The restaurant has seen a lot of temporary changes throughout the show, such as operating [[24/7 service|24/7]] and being transformed into a hotel, which have been the focus of many episodes. Other episodes have depicted the Krusty Krab being damaged or destroyed.\n\n===Krabby Patty===\n{{Main|Krabby Patty}}\nThe Krusty Krab's menu, the Galley Grub, consists mostly of ordinary fast food items, such as french fries and sodas. Its signature sandwich, the [[Krabby Patty]], is celebrated, to a comic degree, by the citizens of Bikini Bottom. In ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]'', Mr. Krabs states: \"The Krabby Patty is what ties us all together! Without it, there will be a complete breakdown of social order!\"<ref>{{cite film|title=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|title-link=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|type=film|date=February 6, 2015|publisher=Paramount Pictures|author=[[Paul Tibbitt|Tibbitt, Paul]] (director)|others=[[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Aibel, Jonathan; Berger, Glenn]] (writers)}}</ref> The sandwich comprises two buns, with the patty, lettuce, cheese, onions, tomatoes, ketchup, mustard, and pickles between them, (in that order).<ref>{{cite episode|title=Pickles|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=1|number=6b|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=August 21, 1999|credits=[[Steven Fonti|Fonti, Steve]]; Mitchell, Chris; Burns, Peter (writers)}}</ref> The recipe of the patty is a closely guarded [[trade secret]], which have led viewers to speculate about its contents.<ref name=\"FoodbeastMSG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/|title=People Think The Krabby Patty's Secret Was Crab Meat, And It Makes So Much Sense|author=Rocha, Isai|date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2019|website=Foodbeast|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171726/https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MetroPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=People think that the secret ingredient in SpongeBob Squarepants\u2019 Krabby Patty is cocaine |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |website=Metro |publisher=DMG Media |accessdate=July 22, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171720/https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several fan theories have been formed to guess the secret ingredient.<ref name=\"SRMeat&Powder\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/|title=SpongeBob Theory: What Are Krabby Patties  Made Of?|author=Hood, Cooper|date=March 16, 2019|accessdate=July 20, 2019|website=Screen Rant|publisher=Valnet Inc.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsweekPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Asarch |first1=Steven |title=SECRET INGREDIENT IN KRABBY PATTY? COCAINE! SAYS INTERNET |url=https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=July 22, 2019 |date=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to animator [[Vincent Waller]], \"there is absolutely no meat in the Krabby Patty. There's no animal product in there\", something which was always planned by series creator [[Stephen Hillenburg]].<ref name=\"CinemablendVegan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows|title=What's In A Krabby Patty? Here's What The Spongebob Producer Knows|author=Joest, Mick|date=July 22, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|website=CinemaBlend|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725193849/http://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows|archive-date=July 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mr. Lawrence]], a show writer and Plankton's voice actor, explained that the show's writers are not allowed to depict [[fish as food]]; he stated that there is no meat served in Bikini Bottom except at the Chum Bucket.<ref name=\"EliteVegan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695|title=Krabby Patty Formula, According To 'Spongebob' Cast Members, Isn't What You Expected|author=Kolokathis, Tina|date=July 23, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2019|website=Elite Daily|publisher=Bustle Digital Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719085317/https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695|archive-date=July 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Tom Kenny]], the voice actor for SpongeBob, joked: \"Krabby Patties are [[hummus]]!\"<ref name=\"EliteVegan\"/> Some commentators suggest that there is no secret ingredient, pointing to Mr. Krabs' miserliness. A writer for [[Hollywood.com]] believes that it is \"all a ruse that crafty Mr. Krabs came up with in order to stop Plankton from focusing on [t]he Chum Bucket. It's legitimately brilliant marketing!\"<ref name=\"HollywoodPowder\">{{cite web |title=We FINALLY Know What The Krabby Patty Secret Formula Is From \u2018SpongeBob\u2019! |url=http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |accessdate=July 22, 2019 |date=May 5, 2016 |website=Hollywood.com |author=Tinubu, Aramide |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615091801/http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |archive-date=June 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the possibility that the secret Krabby Patty formula will be revealed in future episodes, Waller said in 2017 that he \"would not count on it\".<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=881707307071033350 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=I would not count on it. |author=Waller, Vincent |date=July 2, 2017 |access-date=July 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190728104411/https://twitter.com/VincentWaller72/status/881707307071033350 |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Waller stated that Hillenburg{{efn|Stephen Hillenburg died in 2018, making it no longer possible to access the Krabby Patty secret formula}} is the only person to have seen it.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1087776914343845888 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=Yes, but no human has seen it, other than Steve. |author=Waller, Vincent |date=January 22, 2019 |access-date=July 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190728103802/https://twitter.com/VincentWaller72/status/1087776914343845888 |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Lobster trap.jpg|thumb|right|The Krusty Krab's design is based on a [[lobster trap]].]]\nAlong with SpongeBob's pineapple house, the Krusty Krab was originally intended to be where \"the show would return to again and again, and in which most of the action would take place\".<ref name=PittengerHA>{{cite news | author = Pittenger, Kenny | title = The Oral History of ''SpongeBob SquarePants'' | work = [[Hogan's Alley (magazine)|Hogan's Alley]] #17 | year = 2010 | accessdate = September 21, 2012 | url = http://cartoonician.com/the-oral-history-of-spongebob-squarepants/ | publisher = Bull Moose Publishing Corporation | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150831044034/http://cartoonician.com/the-oral-history-of-spongebob-squarepants/ | archive-date = August 31, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> It debuted in \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\", the series premiere, and has since appeared in more than 80% of episodes {{as of|2018|lc=yes}}.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/>\n\nThe Krusty Krab was inspired by series creator Stephen Hillenburg's time as a fry cook and lobster boiler<ref name=\"WalkervViacom\">{{cite web|title=Walker v. Viacom ND Cal May 2008|url=http://www.loeb.com/files/Publication/dc335f53-5049-4947-bccc-0f83952ad07e/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/f3032e0c-c206-42ab-827e-0fa4b30f0be1/Walker%20v%20Viacom%20ND%20Cal%20May%202008.pdf|publisher=United States District Court for the Northern District of California|accessdate=January 12, 2014|date=May 13, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405114908/http://www.loeb.com/files/Publication/dc335f53-5049-4947-bccc-0f83952ad07e/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/f3032e0c-c206-42ab-827e-0fa4b30f0be1/Walker%20v%20Viacom%20ND%20Cal%20May%202008.pdf|archivedate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> at a fast-food seafood restaurant<ref name=\"Current Biography\">{{Cite journal|author=K.E.D.|title=Cover Biography for April 2003|url=http://www.hwwilson.com/Currentbio/cover_bios/cover_bio_4_03.htm|journal=Current Biography| accessdate=December 20, 2013|date=April 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814094924/http://www.hwwilson.com/Currentbio/cover_bios/cover_bio_4_03.htm|archivedate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> during several summers after finishing high school.<ref name=\"Current Biography\"/> SpongeBob's occupation was directly based on this experience,<ref name=\"WalkervViacom\"/> while Mr. Krabs was inspired by Hillenburg's manager at the restaurant.<ref name=\"minipage\">{{cite web|url=http://nieonline.com/coloradonie/downloads/minipage/minipage7.15.15.pdf|title=What a Sponge!|work=[[The Mini Page]]|publisher=[[Andrews McMeel Universal]]|date=July 12, 2015|access-date=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415104043/http://nieonline.com/coloradonie/downloads/minipage/minipage7.15.15.pdf|archive-date=April 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Beck84\"/> However, the restaurant owner was not greedy; Hillenburg added this detail to \"give him more personality\".<ref name=\"minipage\"/>\n\nWhen Hillenburg first created Mr. Krabs, his surname was spelled Crabs, and the name of the restaurant was the Crusty Crab. Hillenburg [[sensational spelling|changed the spelling]] shortly before production began on the show's pilot episode, deciding that K's were funnier and more memorable.<ref name=\"BoytoBob\">{{cite magazine|title=From Boy to Bob|magazine=[[Nickelodeon Magazine|Nick Mag Presents: SpongeBob SquarePants]]|publisher=[[Viacom International]]|date=June 2003}}</ref> He based the building's design on a [[lobster trap]].<ref name=\"Big Pop Fun\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Thomas F. Wilson|Wilson, Tom]] (interviewer); Hillenburg, Stephen (interviewee) |date=May 29, 2012 |title=Big Pop Fun #28: Stephen Hillenburg, Artist and Animator\u2013Interview |url=http://ec.libsyn.com/p/d/9/8/d98c6fd6cc81f188/BPF28_Stephen_Hillenburg_artist_and_animator.mp3?d13a76d516d9dec20c3d276ce028ed5089ab1ce3dae902ea1d01c08031d1c85f7cb2&c_id=4560686 |format=mp3 |medium=Podcast |publisher=Nerdist Industries |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6M1QBJ1BZ?url=http://ec.libsyn.com/p/d/9/8/d98c6fd6cc81f188/BPF28_Stephen_Hillenburg_artist_and_animator.mp3?d13a76d516d9dec20c3d276ce028ed5089ab1ce3dae902ea1d01c08031d1c85f7cb2&c_id=4560686 |archivedate=December 21, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances in other media==\nThe restaurant was featured in the 2004 theatrical film ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' and its [[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|2015 follow-up]] (where the secret Krabby Patty formula was a major [[plot device]]). It has been adapted to [[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|Broadway]]. The Krusty Krab and the Krabby Patty have been referenced or parodied throughout popular culture. In \"[[Robot Chicken (season 5)##ep87|Major League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]\", an episode of the sketch comedy ''[[Robot Chicken]]'', a segment features Mr. Krabs using crab legs as the secret ingredient for Krabby Patties.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Major League of Extraordinary Gentlemen|series=Robot Chicken|season=5|number=87|network=Adult Swim|airdate=February 13, 2011|credits=Beans, Matthew; [[Mike Fasolo|Fasolo, Mike]]; [[Seth Green|Green, Seth]]; Hay, Brendan; Libman, Daniel; Libman, Matthew; [[Matthew Senreich|Senreich, Matthew]]; [[Zeb Wells|Wells, Zeb]] (writers)}}</ref> Online, the Krusty Krab\u2013Chum Bucket rivalry has been turned into [[Internet meme|memes]].<ref name=\"Mashable meme\">{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/03/19/krusty-krab-vs-chum-bucket-spongebob-meme/|author=Bryan, Chloe|title=Use the 'Krusty Krab vs. Chum Bucket' meme to share your strongest takes|date=March 19, 2018|website=Mashable|accessdate=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717150549/https://mashable.com/2018/03/19/krusty-krab-vs-chum-bucket-spongebob-meme/|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/03/the-krusty-krabchum-bucket-rivalry-spongebob-meme-explained.html|title=The Krusty Krab\u2013Chum Bucket Rivalry Meme Is the Perfect Meme for Declaring Winners and Losers|accessdate=July 18, 2019|date=March 19, 2018|work=New York|publisher=New York Media|author=Kircher, Madison Malone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517092510/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/03/the-krusty-krabchum-bucket-rivalry-spongebob-meme-explained.html|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Krusty Krab has been included in many ''SpongeBob SquarePants'' toys, publications, and other [[List of SpongeBob SquarePants merchandise|merchandise]]. [[The Lego Group]] has released two [[Lego]] construction sets modeled after the Krusty Krab building.<ref>{{cite web |title=3825 The Krusty Krab |url=http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/Products/SpongeBob/3825.aspx |publisher=The Lego Group |accessdate=August 11, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070813230029/http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/Products/SpongeBob/3825.aspx |archivedate=August 13, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=3833 Krusty Krab Adventures|url=http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/products/spongebob/3833/|publisher=The Lego Group|accessdate=May 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505051029/http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/products/spongebob/3833|archive-date=May 5, 2013}}</ref> The Krusty Krab has also appeared in ''SpongeBob''-related video games, such as ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants: Creature from the Krusty Krab]]'', the title of which alludes to the restaurant. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]], which owns [[Nickelodeon]], has earned millions of dollars on licensed products bearing the Krusty Krab name, mainly aquarium figurines and children's play sets.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/>\n\n== Cultural impact ==\n\n===Reception===\nThe Krusty Krab has been recognized by numerous publications\u2014including [[BuzzFeed]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tarallo |first1=Kaitlyn |title=13 Cartoon Restaurants You Wish Were Real |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/kaitt18/13-cartoon-restaurants-you-wish-were-real-1561r |website=BuzzFeed|accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=April 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415010243/http://www.buzzfeed.com/kaitt18/13-cartoon-restaurants-you-wish-were-real-1561r |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> the [[New York Daily News|New York ''Daily News'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/best-fictional-restaurants-gallery-1.3358512|title=Good Burgers: A look at the best fictional restaurants|accessdate=July 18, 2019|date=July 29, 2017|work=New York Daily News|publisher=Tribune Publishing|author=Bodner, Brett|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718035105/https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/best-fictional-restaurants-gallery-1.3358512|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Screen Rant]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanders |first1=Georgia |title=14 Fictional Restaurants We Wish We Could Eat At |url=https://screenrant.com/best-fictional-restaurant-movies-tv/ |website=Screen Rant |publisher=Valnet Inc. |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=February 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719075426/https://screenrant.com/best-fictional-restaurant-movies-tv/ |archive-date=July 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and food website ''[[The Daily Meal]]''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Menyes |first1=Carolyn |title=15 TV Restaurants We Wish Were Real Gallery |url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/best-tv-restaurants-slideshow |website=The Daily Meal |publisher=Spanfeller Media Group |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=March 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710224932/https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/best-tv-restaurants-slideshow |archive-date=July 10, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\u2014as a restaurant they wished were real. Similarly, as stated in [[Boston.com]], \"Sure, we can get crab cakes, but we wish we could try the Krusty Krab's signature sandwich, the Krabby Patties. If only we could get a suit like [[Sandy Cheeks|Sandy]]'s and journey to Bikini Bottom\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/tv/cartoon_things_we_wish_were_real?pg=7|title=Cartoon-eality: If cartoons came to life|year=2013|website=Boston.com|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners|accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> In another list published by ''The Daily Meal'', the Krusty Krab was voted number one of \"all the fictional spots currently on TV that our readers wished they could dine at\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gordon |first1=Lauren |title=Favorite TV Hangout Spots: On Air Now (Slideshow) |url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/favorite-tv-hangout-spots-air-now-slideshow/slide-10 |website=The Daily Meal |publisher=Spanfeller Media Group |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=August 30, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719075422/https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/favorite-tv-hangout-spots-air-now-slideshow/slide-10 |archive-date=July 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine listed the Krusty Krab as one of the 18 most influential fictional companies.<ref name=\"infl comp\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4351022/influential-fake-companies/|title=The 18 Most Influential Fake Companies of All Time|accessdate=June 7, 2016|date=June 2, 2016|work=Time|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602175058/http://time.com/4351022/influential-fake-companies/?xid=homepage|archivedate=June 2, 2016|first1=Alex|last1=Fitzpatrick|first2=Matt|last2=Vella|first3=Lisa|last3=Eadicicco|first4=Matt|last4=Peckham|first5=John Patrick|last5=Pullen|first6=Sarah|last6=Begley|first7=Daniel|last7=D'Addario}}</ref>\n\n===Real-life versions===\n====Imitations====\n{{external media\n|width   = 200px\n|image1  = [https://web.archive.org/web/20190718102846/http://www.yummypick.com/wp-content/uploads//2014/10/Krusty-Krab-1--dcc8b2bd731f04fd960d449177e218d8.jpg View of the exterior of Salta Burgers' real-life Krusty Krab replica in Ramallah]\n|image2  = [https://web.archive.org/web/20190718103518/http://www.yummypick.com/wp-content/uploads//2014/10/Krusty-Krab-2--fec1fe3d954306a9982abf58c2f028c7.jpg Scene inside the building] with tables, chairs, cash register booth, and other detailing similar to those of the television series.\n}}\nThe Krusty Krab has inspired several real-life establishments unaffiliated with Nickelodeon or its parent company, Viacom. In [[Monteverde|Santa Elena]], Costa Rica, a restaurant called the Krusty Krab opened in 2012 but closed a year later.<ref name=\"HeavyPalestine\">{{cite web |last1=Morgan |first1=Emily |title=Krusty Krab in Palestine: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2014/07/krusty-krab-restaurant-spongebob-squarepants-palestine-salta-burgers/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=April 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718003939/https://heavy.com/entertainment/2014/07/krusty-krab-restaurant-spongebob-squarepants-palestine-salta-burgers/ |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Ramallah]], Palestine, a company called Salta Burgers constructed a real-life Krusty Krab,<ref name=\"WPPalestine\">{{cite web |last1=McDonald |first1=Soraya Nadia |title='SpongeBob's' Krusty Krab is opening \u2014 in the West Bank |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/07/22/spongebobs-krusty-krab-is-opening-in-palestine/ |website=The Washington Post |publisher=Nash Holdings |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=July 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"THRPalestine\">{{cite news | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/photos-krusty-krab-restaurant-open-719889 | title='SpongeBob SquarePants': Real-Life Krusty Krab Restaurant to Open in Palestine | work=The Hollywood Reporter | date=July 21, 2014 | accessdate=August 12, 2014 | author=Nordyke, Kimberly | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811145501/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/photos-krusty-krab-restaurant-open-719889 | archive-date=August 11, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> which received online attention.<ref name=\"ElitePalestine\">{{cite web |last1=Anthony |first1=Robert |title=The Real-Life Krusty Krab Has Left Bikini Bottom And Is Now Open In Palestine (Photos) |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/envision/food/krusty-krab-now-open/710287 |website=Elite Daily |publisher=Bustle Digital Group |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718095341/https://www.elitedaily.com/envision/food/krusty-krab-now-open/710287 |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It opened on July{{nbsp}}24, 2014,<ref name=\"FusionPalestine\">{{cite web|title=Inside the Krusty Krab restaurant now open for business in Palestine|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vyfozQGnne0|website=Fusion TV|publisher=Univision Communications|accessdate=July 17, 2019|date=December 16, 2014|via=YouTube|format=video|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427145333/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vyfozQGnne0|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> serving seafood and its own version of the Krabby Patty;<ref name=\"HeavyPalestine\"/><ref name=\"THRPalestine\"/><ref name=\"TOIPalestine\">{{cite web |title=Spongebob-themed eatery hits Ramallah |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ramallahs-spongebob-themed-eatery/ |website=The Times of Israel |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=June 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717182227/https://www.timesofisrael.com/ramallahs-spongebob-themed-eatery/ |archive-date=July 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2017|lc=yes}}, the restaurant is still in operation.<ref name=\"HuffPalestine\">{{cite web |title=Your Favorite Cartoon Foods Are Now Available To Eat IRL |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/your-favorite-cartoon-foo_b_9533682 |website=HuffPost |publisher=Verizon Media |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=March 23, 2016}}</ref> Some commentators, like in the ''[[Houston Press]]'' noted of these foreign imitations that \"The long arm of U.S. trademark law doesn't reach across international waters. Every country has its own filing process that must be followed\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Phaedra |title=Viacom Sues Houston Firm, Says It Can't Use The Krusty Krab Name From SpongeBob SquarePants |url=https://www.houstonpress.com/restaurants/things-to-do-upcoming-food-and-drink-events-in-houston-this-week-11320757 |website=Houston Press |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=February 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716161850/https://www.houstonpress.com/restaurants/things-to-do-upcoming-food-and-drink-events-in-houston-this-week-11320757 |archive-date=July 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Moscow]], a Krusty Krab-[[theme restaurant|themed restaurant]] called The Krusty Krab Cafe opened in 2016 and also makes unofficial Krabby Patties.<ref name=\"MetroMoscow\">{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/02/22/a-real-life-version-of-the-krusty-krab-restaurant-from-spongebob-squarepants-has-just-opened-5711591/ |title=There's a new real-life version of the cafe from Spongebob Squarepants |work=Metro |date=February 22, 2016 |accessdate=May 12, 2019 |author=Hardingham-Gill, Tamara |publisher=DMG Media |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630081229/https://metro.co.uk/2016/02/22/a-real-life-version-of-the-krusty-krab-restaurant-from-spongebob-squarepants-has-just-opened-5711591/ |archive-date=June 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Davao City]], Philippines, a coffee shop opened in 2017 and sells Krabby Patty-inspired sandwiches; it was named KrustyKrub Cafe because the son of its husband-and-wife owners is a fan of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/164654|title=KrustyKrub Cafe: Business proposal turned into reality|first=Ivy C.|last=Tejano|work=SunStar|date=September 18, 2017|accessdate=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717182232/https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/164654|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Viacom sued IJR Capital Investments after learning that it had applied to trademark the Krusty Krab name at the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office|U.S. Patent and Trademark Office]] (USPTO) in December 2014.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\">{{cite web |last1=Langford |first1=Cameron |title=Judge Says Restaurant Can't Be Called 'Krusty Krab' |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-says-restaurant-cant-be-called-krusty-krab/ |publisher=Courthouse News Service |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=January 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207135014/https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-says-restaurant-cant-be-called-krusty-krab/ |archive-date=February 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The latter was planning to open two restaurants adopting the moniker in Houston and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\">{{cite web |last1=Langford |first1=Cameron |title=Fifth Circuit Rules for Viacom in 'Krusty Krab' Restaurant Case |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/fifth-circuit-rules-for-viacom-in-krusty-krab-restaurant-case/ |publisher=Courthouse News Service |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=May 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225195347/https://www.courthousenews.com/fifth-circuit-rules-for-viacom-in-krusty-krab-restaurant-case/ |archive-date=December 25, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the lawsuit, Viacom claimed that the proposed restaurants would be an infringement, even though Viacom had not filed a formal trademark for the Krusty Krab name.<ref name=\"ViceRamos\">{{cite web |last1=Sen |first1=Mayukh |title=Nickelodeon Forbids Man from Naming Restaurant 'Krusty Krab' |url=https://www.vice.com/en_asia/article/gy8qm7/nickelodeon-forbids-man-from-naming-restaurant-krusty-krab |publisher=Vice Media |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> IJR owner, Javier Ramos Jr. claimed he thought of the name, referring to \"the crust that sticks to the top of crabs when they are put in a seafood boil\".<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/> He claimed not to have heard of the Krusty Krab in ''SpongeBob SquarePants'', and that he chose it after checking Google and finding no restaurants using that name.<ref name=\"ReutersRamos\">{{cite web|title=Viacom's SpongeBob keeps rights to Krusty Krab restaurant name|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/viacom-lawsuit-spongebob/viacoms-spongebob-keeps-rights-to-krusty-krab-restaurant-name-idUSL2N1ST1QD|website=Reuters|first=Jonathan|last=Stempel|accessdate=July 18, 2019|date=May 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524093252/https://www.reuters.com/article/viacom-lawsuit-spongebob/viacoms-spongebob-keeps-rights-to-krusty-krab-restaurant-name-idUSL2N1ST1QD|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While the USPTO approved IJR's trademark application,<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\"/><ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/> a Texas federal judge ruled in January 2017 that IJR violated Viacom's rights to the ''SpongeBob'' property,<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-rules-krusty-krab-restaurant-violates-viacoms-spongebob-rights-963632|title=Judge Rules 'Krusty Krab' Restaurant Violates Viacom's 'SpongeBob' Rights|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 11, 2017|last=Gardner|first=Eriq|access-date=January 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113152713/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-rules-krusty-krab-restaurant-violates-viacoms-spongebob-rights-963632|archive-date=January 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2017/01/12/spongebob-and-krusty-krab-prevail-in-real-life-trademark-battle/|title=SpongeBob and Krusty Krab Prevail in Real-Life Trademark Battle|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=January 12, 2017|last=Gershman|first=Jacob|access-date=August 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116025214/https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2017/01/12/spongebob-and-krusty-krab-prevail-in-real-life-trademark-battle/|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> citing \"ownership of a trademark is established by use, not by registration\".<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\"/> The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] decided in May 2018 that Viacom deserves trademark protection for the Krusty Krab, and that IJR cannot use it.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/><ref name=\"ReutersRamos\"/>\n\n====San Diego Comic-Con 2019====\n[[File:Krusty Krab exhibit (48344458757).jpg|thumb|right|Nickelodeon's Krusty Krab replica at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\nIn celebration of the 20th anniversary of ''SpongeBob'', Nickelodeon recreated the Krusty Krab building at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]].<ref name=\"AltPressSDCC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/spongebob-nickelodeon-bikini-bottom-comic-con/|title=SPONGEBOB ANNIVERSARY HONORED WITH REPLICA BIKINI BOTTOM AT COMIC-CON|author=Darus, Alex|date=July 18, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|website=Alternative Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718212356/https://www.altpress.com/news/spongebob-nickelodeon-bikini-bottom-comic-con/|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/m/star-wars-episode-ix/134769/news/77-photos-of-star-wars-avengers-the-witcher-and-more-from-the-sdcc-show-floor-comic-con-2019|title=77 Photos of Star Wars, Avengers, The Witcher and More From the SDCC Show Floor - Comic-Con 2019|author=Collura, Scott|publisher=IGN|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719025312/https://za.ign.com/m/star-wars-episode-ix/134769/news/77-photos-of-star-wars-avengers-the-witcher-and-more-from-the-sdcc-show-floor-comic-con-2019|archive-date=July 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Inside, attendees could play an interactive game in which they must complete food orders before running out of time.<ref name=\"DeadlineSDCC\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/spongebob-squarepants-san-diego-comic-con-20th-anniversary-1202634218/|title='SpongeBob SquarePants' 20th Anniversary To Pop Confetti At San Diego Comic-Con|author=D'Alessandro, Anthony|date=June 18, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630092536/https://deadline.com/2019/06/spongebob-squarepants-san-diego-comic-con-20th-anniversary-1202634218/|archive-date=June 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"SRSDCC\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/spongebob-squarepants-20th-anniversary-san-diego-comic-con-2019/amp/|title=SpongeBob Celebrating 20th Anniversary At San Diego Comic-Con 2019|author=Tyler, Adrienne|date=June 18, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|website=Screen Rant|publisher=Valnet Inc.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719025311/https://screenrant.com/spongebob-squarepants-20th-anniversary-san-diego-comic-con-2019/amp/|archive-date=July 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was part of Nickelodeon's {{convert|1800|ft2|m2|adj=on}} booth<ref name=\"DeadlineSDCC\" /> at the event, which was dedicated to the show.<ref name=\"AltPressSDCC\" /> It featured real-life replicas of [[Mrs. Puff]]'s Boating School and the Chum Bucket, which stood {{convert|22|ft|m}} tall and allowed attendees to buy collectibles and have autographs from the show's [[List of SpongeBob SquarePants cast members|cast members]].<ref name=\"DeadlineSDCC\"/><ref name=\"SRSDCC\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that the Bikini Bottom setup \"drew hundreds of nostalgic fans\" on the first day of the convention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-07-19/la-et-comic-con-sponge-bob-stephen-hillenburg|title=\u2018SpongeBob\u2019 actors get tearful remembering creator Stephen Hillenburg at Comic-Con|author=Schoellkopf, Christina|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=July 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725195830/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-07-19/la-et-comic-con-sponge-bob-stephen-hillenburg|archive-date=July 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Adweek]]'' named it among its ten \"Favorite TV-Themed Activations at Comic-Con 2019\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/our-10-favorite-tv-themed-activations-at-comic-con-2019/|title=Our 10 Favorite TV-Themed Activations at Comic-Con 2019|work=Adweek|publisher=Beringer Capital|author=Jerde, Sara|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=July 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726071006/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/our-10-favorite-tv-themed-activations-at-comic-con-2019/|archive-date=July 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Beck84\">{{harvnb|Beck|2013|page=84}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aPRymAEACAAJ|title=The SpongeBob SquarePants Experience: A Deep Dive Into the World of Bikini Bottom|publisher=Insight Editions|last=Beck|first=Jerry|author-link=Jerry Beck|date=2013|isbn=978-1-60887-184-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|Nickelodeon}}\n\n*{{Facebook|TheKrustyKrabOfficial}}\n\n{{SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional restaurants]]\n[[Category:SpongeBob SquarePants]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-sock|small=yes}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|Fictional restaurant in SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n{{Infobox fictional business \n| name       = The Krusty Krab\n| image      = Krusty Krab 230b.png\n| image_size = 240px\n| caption    =\n| series     = ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''\n| first      = \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\" (1999)\n| type       = [[Fast food restaurant]]\n| owner      = [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene Krabs]]<!-- DO NOT add Viacom or other real-world companies as the owner.-->\n| founded    =\n| location   = [[Bikini Bottom]]\n| employees  = {{plainlist|\n* [[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob SquarePants]] ([[fry cook]])\n* [[Squidward Tentacles]] ([[cashier]])\n}}\n| products   = [[Krabby Patty|Krabby Patties]]\n| slogan    = \"Come Spend Your Money Here!\"<ref name=\"As Seen on TV\">{{cite episode|title=As Seen on TV|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=3|number=47a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=March 8, 2002|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Merriwether Williams|Williams, Merriwether]] (writers)}}</ref><!-- Slogan given in \"As Seen on TV\", so don't remove it. -->\n}}\n\nThe '''Krusty Krab''' is a fictional [[fast food restaurant]] in the American animated television series ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''. It is famous for its signature burger, the [[Krabby Patty]], the formula to which is a closely guarded [[trade secret]].\n\nThe restaurant was founded by [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene H. Krabs]] (Mr. Krabs), who is also the owner and manager. It has two full-time employees: [[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob SquarePants]], who works as the [[chef|fry cook]]; and [[Squidward Tentacles]], who works as the [[cashier]]. The Krusty Krab is deemed \"the finest eating establishment ever established for eating\" in [[Bikini Bottom]], and it is constantly challenged by its primary competitor, the [[Chum Bucket (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Chum Bucket]], which is operated by Mr. Krabs' [[archenemy|nemesis]] and former best friend, [[Plankton and Karen#Plankton|Plankton]].\n\nOne of the main settings of the series, the Krusty Krab was introduced in the pilot episode, \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\", where SpongeBob applies for the fry cook job at the restaurant. The Krusty Krab has also been featured in other media, including a [[SpongeBob SquarePants (film series)|theatrical film series]], a [[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|Broadway musical]], video games, and toys. The restaurant has been referenced or parodied throughout popular culture. It has also inspired real-life establishments.\n\n==Role in ''SpongeBob SquarePants''==\n[[File:Krusty Krab interior 50b.png|thumb|left|Inside the restaurant, Squidward is working the cash register, and various characters are eating Krabby Patties.]]\nThe Krusty Krab is a prominent fast food restaurant in the underwater city of [[Bikini Bottom]]. It is owned and operated by [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene H. Krabs]] (Mr. Krabs), who invented its famous Krabby Patty sandwich.<ref name=\"Friend or Foe\">{{cite episode|title=[[Friend or Foe (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Friend or Foe]]|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=5|number=81|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=April 13, 2007|credits=[[Casey Alexander (cartoonist)|Alexander, Casey]]; Cervas, Zeus; [[Mike Mitchell (director)|Mitchell, Mike]]; [[Steven Banks|Banks, Steven]]; [[Tim Hill (director)|Hill, Tim]] (writers)}}</ref> Mr. Krabs has two employees: [[Squidward Tentacles]] and [[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob SquarePants]], who work as the [[cashier]] and [[chef|fry cook]], respectively. [[Patrick Star]] has also worked at the Krusty Krab for several brief stints in a variety of positions.\n\nLocated across the street from the Krusty Krab is the Chum Bucket, another fast food restaurant owned and operated by [[Plankton and Karen]].<ref name=\"Friend or Foe\"/> Plankton, Mr. Krabs' former best friend,<ref name=\"Friend or Foe\"/> later became his arch-competitor;<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Algae's Always Greener|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=3|number=41a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=March 22, 2002|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Merriwether Williams|Williams, Merriwether]] (writers)}}</ref> Plankton's futile attempts at stealing the secret Krabby Patty recipe to replicate the burgers and put the Krusty Krab out of business is a major plot point throughout the series.\n\nThe Krusty Krab usually attracts customers from Bikini Bottom because of the Krabby Patty's renowned taste and the fact that Plankton's restaurant has a menu consisting of [[chumming|chum]] (bait consisting of fish parts), which is considered mostly inedible by the other characters.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Chum Bucket Supreme|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=6|number=122a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=July 19, 2009|credits=Charmatz, Sean; [[Dani Michaeli|Michaeli, Dani]] (writers)}}</ref> As a result, the Krusty Krab has become one of the most successful restaurants in the city.<ref name=\"Hist\"/> In the show, SpongeBob calls it \"the finest eating establishment ever established for eating\".<ref>{{cite episode|title=[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=1|number=1a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=May 1, 1999|credits=[[Stephen Hillenburg|Hillenburg, Stephen]]; [[Derek Drymon|Drymon, Derek]]; [[Tim Hill (director)|Hill, Tim]] (writers)}}</ref> Mr. Krabs frequently exploits his restaurant's popularity, such as engaging in [[price gouging]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Krusty Sponge|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=5|number=89a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=July 24, 2007|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; Shaw, Eric (writers)}}</ref> and charging his own employees for use of the building's services.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Squid on Strike|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=2|number=40a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=October 12, 2001|credits=[[Walt Dohrn|Dohrn, Walt]]; [[Paul Tibbitt|Tibbitt, Paul]]; [[Mark O'Hare|O'Hare, Mark]] (writers)}}</ref>\n\nIn one episode, the Krusty Krab building is shown to have originally been a run-down retirement home called the Rusty Krab, which Mr. Krabs acquired and converted into a restaurant.<ref name=\"Hist\">{{cite episode|title=Krusty Krab Training Video|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=3|number=50b|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=May 10, 2002|credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Kent Osborne|Osborne, Kent]] (writers)}}</ref> In another episode, the restaurant was also the name of a pirate ship owned by Mr. Krabs before he started the business.<ref name=\"Grandpappy the Pirate\">{{cite episode|title=Grandpappy the Pirate|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=6|number=115a|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=February 18, 2009|credits=[[Casey Alexander (cartoonist)|Alexander, Casey]]; Cervas, Zeus; [[Dani Michaeli|Michaeli, Dani]] (writers)}}</ref> The restaurant has seen a lot of temporary changes throughout the show, such as operating [[24/7 service|24/7]] and being transformed into a hotel, which have been the focus of many episodes. Other episodes have depicted the Krusty Krab being damaged or destroyed.\n\n===Krabby Patty===\n{{Main|Krabby Patty}}\nThe Krusty Krab's menu, the Galley Grub, consists mostly of ordinary fast food items, such as french fries and sodas. Its signature sandwich, the [[Krabby Patty]], is celebrated, to a comic degree, by the citizens of Bikini Bottom. In ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]'', Mr. Krabs states: \"The Krabby Patty is what ties us all together! Without it, there will be a complete breakdown of social order!\"<ref>{{cite film|title=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|title-link=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|type=film|date=February 6, 2015|publisher=Paramount Pictures|author=[[Paul Tibbitt|Tibbitt, Paul]] (director)|others=[[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Aibel, Jonathan; Berger, Glenn]] (writers)}}</ref> The sandwich comprises two buns, with the patty, lettuce, cheese, onions, tomatoes, ketchup, mustard, and pickles between them, (in that order).<ref>{{cite episode|title=Pickles|series=SpongeBob SquarePants|season=1|number=6b|network=Nickelodeon|airdate=August 21, 1999|credits=[[Steven Fonti|Fonti, Steve]]; Mitchell, Chris; Burns, Peter (writers)}}</ref> The recipe of the patty is a closely guarded [[trade secret]], which have led viewers to speculate about its contents.<ref name=\"FoodbeastMSG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/|title=People Think The Krabby Patty's Secret Was Crab Meat, And It Makes So Much Sense|author=Rocha, Isai|date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2019|website=Foodbeast|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171726/https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MetroPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=People think that the secret ingredient in SpongeBob Squarepants\u2019 Krabby Patty is cocaine |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |website=Metro |publisher=DMG Media |accessdate=July 22, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171720/https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several fan theories have been formed to guess the secret ingredient.<ref name=\"SRMeat&Powder\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/|title=SpongeBob Theory: What Are Krabby Patties Actually Made Of?|author=Hood, Cooper|date=March 16, 2019|accessdate=July 20, 2019|website=Screen Rant|publisher=Valnet Inc.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsweekPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Asarch |first1=Steven |title=SECRET INGREDIENT IN KRABBY PATTY? COCAINE! SAYS INTERNET |url=https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=July 22, 2019 |date=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to animator [[Vincent Waller]], \"there is absolutely no meat in the Krabby Patty. There's no animal product in there\", something which was always planned by series creator [[Stephen Hillenburg]].<ref name=\"CinemablendVegan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows|title=What's In A Krabby Patty? Here's What The Spongebob Producer Knows|author=Joest, Mick|date=July 22, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|website=CinemaBlend|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725193849/http://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows|archive-date=July 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mr. Lawrence]], a show writer and Plankton's voice actor, explained that the show's writers are not allowed to depict [[fish as food]]; he stated that there is no meat served in Bikini Bottom except at the Chum Bucket.<ref name=\"EliteVegan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695|title=Krabby Patty Formula, According To 'Spongebob' Cast Members, Isn't What You Expected|author=Kolokathis, Tina|date=July 23, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2019|website=Elite Daily|publisher=Bustle Digital Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719085317/https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695|archive-date=July 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Tom Kenny]], the voice actor for SpongeBob, joked: \"Krabby Patties are [[hummus]]!\"<ref name=\"EliteVegan\"/> Some commentators suggest that there is actually no secret ingredient, pointing to Mr. Krabs' miserliness. A writer for [[Hollywood.com]] believes that it is \"all a ruse that crafty Mr. Krabs came up with in order to stop Plankton from focusing on [t]he Chum Bucket. It's legitimately brilliant marketing!\"<ref name=\"HollywoodPowder\">{{cite web |title=We FINALLY Know What The Krabby Patty Secret Formula Is From \u2018SpongeBob\u2019! |url=http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |accessdate=July 22, 2019 |date=May 5, 2016 |website=Hollywood.com |author=Tinubu, Aramide |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615091801/http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |archive-date=June 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the possibility that the secret Krabby Patty formula will be revealed in future episodes, Waller said in 2017 that he \"would not count on it\".<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=881707307071033350 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=I would not count on it. |author=Waller, Vincent |date=July 2, 2017 |access-date=July 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190728104411/https://twitter.com/VincentWaller72/status/881707307071033350 |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Waller stated that Hillenburg{{efn|Stephen Hillenburg died in 2018, making it no longer possible to access the Krabby Patty secret formula}} is the only person to have seen it.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1087776914343845888 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=Yes, but no human has seen it, other than Steve. |author=Waller, Vincent |date=January 22, 2019 |access-date=July 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190728103802/https://twitter.com/VincentWaller72/status/1087776914343845888 |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Lobster trap.jpg|thumb|right|The Krusty Krab's design is based on a [[lobster trap]].]]\nAlong with SpongeBob's pineapple house, the Krusty Krab was originally intended to be where \"the show would return to again and again, and in which most of the action would take place\".<ref name=PittengerHA>{{cite news | author = Pittenger, Kenny | title = The Oral History of ''SpongeBob SquarePants'' | work = [[Hogan's Alley (magazine)|Hogan's Alley]] #17 | year = 2010 | accessdate = September 21, 2012 | url = http://cartoonician.com/the-oral-history-of-spongebob-squarepants/ | publisher = Bull Moose Publishing Corporation | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150831044034/http://cartoonician.com/the-oral-history-of-spongebob-squarepants/ | archive-date = August 31, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> It debuted in \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\", the series premiere, and has since appeared in more than 80% of episodes {{as of|2018|lc=yes}}.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/>\n\nThe Krusty Krab was inspired by series creator Stephen Hillenburg's time as a fry cook and lobster boiler<ref name=\"WalkervViacom\">{{cite web|title=Walker v. Viacom ND Cal May 2008|url=http://www.loeb.com/files/Publication/dc335f53-5049-4947-bccc-0f83952ad07e/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/f3032e0c-c206-42ab-827e-0fa4b30f0be1/Walker%20v%20Viacom%20ND%20Cal%20May%202008.pdf|publisher=United States District Court for the Northern District of California|accessdate=January 12, 2014|date=May 13, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405114908/http://www.loeb.com/files/Publication/dc335f53-5049-4947-bccc-0f83952ad07e/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/f3032e0c-c206-42ab-827e-0fa4b30f0be1/Walker%20v%20Viacom%20ND%20Cal%20May%202008.pdf|archivedate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> at a fast-food seafood restaurant<ref name=\"Current Biography\">{{Cite journal|author=K.E.D.|title=Cover Biography for April 2003|url=http://www.hwwilson.com/Currentbio/cover_bios/cover_bio_4_03.htm|journal=Current Biography| accessdate=December 20, 2013|date=April 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814094924/http://www.hwwilson.com/Currentbio/cover_bios/cover_bio_4_03.htm|archivedate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> during several summers after finishing high school.<ref name=\"Current Biography\"/> SpongeBob's occupation was directly based on this experience,<ref name=\"WalkervViacom\"/> while Mr. Krabs was inspired by Hillenburg's manager at the restaurant.<ref name=\"minipage\">{{cite web|url=http://nieonline.com/coloradonie/downloads/minipage/minipage7.15.15.pdf|title=What a Sponge!|work=[[The Mini Page]]|publisher=[[Andrews McMeel Universal]]|date=July 12, 2015|access-date=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415104043/http://nieonline.com/coloradonie/downloads/minipage/minipage7.15.15.pdf|archive-date=April 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Beck84\"/> However, the restaurant owner was not greedy; Hillenburg added this detail to \"give him more personality\".<ref name=\"minipage\"/>\n\nWhen Hillenburg first created Mr. Krabs, his surname was spelled Crabs, and the name of the restaurant was the Crusty Crab. Hillenburg [[sensational spelling|changed the spelling]] shortly before production began on the show's pilot episode, deciding that K's were funnier and more memorable.<ref name=\"BoytoBob\">{{cite magazine|title=From Boy to Bob|magazine=[[Nickelodeon Magazine|Nick Mag Presents: SpongeBob SquarePants]]|publisher=[[Viacom International]]|date=June 2003}}</ref> He based the building's design on a [[lobster trap]].<ref name=\"Big Pop Fun\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Thomas F. Wilson|Wilson, Tom]] (interviewer); Hillenburg, Stephen (interviewee) |date=May 29, 2012 |title=Big Pop Fun #28: Stephen Hillenburg, Artist and Animator\u2013Interview |url=http://ec.libsyn.com/p/d/9/8/d98c6fd6cc81f188/BPF28_Stephen_Hillenburg_artist_and_animator.mp3?d13a76d516d9dec20c3d276ce028ed5089ab1ce3dae902ea1d01c08031d1c85f7cb2&c_id=4560686 |format=mp3 |medium=Podcast |publisher=Nerdist Industries |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6M1QBJ1BZ?url=http://ec.libsyn.com/p/d/9/8/d98c6fd6cc81f188/BPF28_Stephen_Hillenburg_artist_and_animator.mp3?d13a76d516d9dec20c3d276ce028ed5089ab1ce3dae902ea1d01c08031d1c85f7cb2&c_id=4560686 |archivedate=December 21, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances in other media==\nThe restaurant was featured in the 2004 theatrical film ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' and its [[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|2015 follow-up]] (where the secret Krabby Patty formula was a major [[plot device]]). It has been adapted to [[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|Broadway]]. The Krusty Krab and the Krabby Patty have been referenced or parodied throughout popular culture. In \"[[Robot Chicken (season 5)##ep87|Major League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]\", an episode of the sketch comedy ''[[Robot Chicken]]'', a segment features Mr. Krabs using crab legs as the secret ingredient for Krabby Patties.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Major League of Extraordinary Gentlemen|series=Robot Chicken|season=5|number=87|network=Adult Swim|airdate=February 13, 2011|credits=Beans, Matthew; [[Mike Fasolo|Fasolo, Mike]]; [[Seth Green|Green, Seth]]; Hay, Brendan; Libman, Daniel; Libman, Matthew; [[Matthew Senreich|Senreich, Matthew]]; [[Zeb Wells|Wells, Zeb]] (writers)}}</ref> Online, the Krusty Krab\u2013Chum Bucket rivalry has been turned into [[Internet meme|memes]].<ref name=\"Mashable meme\">{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/03/19/krusty-krab-vs-chum-bucket-spongebob-meme/|author=Bryan, Chloe|title=Use the 'Krusty Krab vs. Chum Bucket' meme to share your strongest takes|date=March 19, 2018|website=Mashable|accessdate=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717150549/https://mashable.com/2018/03/19/krusty-krab-vs-chum-bucket-spongebob-meme/|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/03/the-krusty-krabchum-bucket-rivalry-spongebob-meme-explained.html|title=The Krusty Krab\u2013Chum Bucket Rivalry Meme Is the Perfect Meme for Declaring Winners and Losers|accessdate=July 18, 2019|date=March 19, 2018|work=New York|publisher=New York Media|author=Kircher, Madison Malone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517092510/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/03/the-krusty-krabchum-bucket-rivalry-spongebob-meme-explained.html|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Krusty Krab has been included in many ''SpongeBob SquarePants'' toys, publications, and other [[List of SpongeBob SquarePants merchandise|merchandise]]. [[The Lego Group]] has released two [[Lego]] construction sets modeled after the Krusty Krab building.<ref>{{cite web |title=3825 The Krusty Krab |url=http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/Products/SpongeBob/3825.aspx |publisher=The Lego Group |accessdate=August 11, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070813230029/http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/Products/SpongeBob/3825.aspx |archivedate=August 13, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=3833 Krusty Krab Adventures|url=http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/products/spongebob/3833/|publisher=The Lego Group|accessdate=May 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505051029/http://spongebob.lego.com/en-us/products/spongebob/3833|archive-date=May 5, 2013}}</ref> The Krusty Krab has also appeared in ''SpongeBob''-related video games, such as ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants: Creature from the Krusty Krab]]'', the title of which alludes to the restaurant. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]], which owns [[Nickelodeon]], has earned millions of dollars on licensed products bearing the Krusty Krab name, mainly aquarium figurines and children's play sets.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/>\n\n== Cultural impact ==\n\n===Reception===\nThe Krusty Krab has been recognized by numerous publications\u2014including [[BuzzFeed]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tarallo |first1=Kaitlyn |title=13 Cartoon Restaurants You Wish Were Real |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/kaitt18/13-cartoon-restaurants-you-wish-were-real-1561r |website=BuzzFeed|accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=April 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415010243/http://www.buzzfeed.com/kaitt18/13-cartoon-restaurants-you-wish-were-real-1561r |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> the [[New York Daily News|New York ''Daily News'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/best-fictional-restaurants-gallery-1.3358512|title=Good Burgers: A look at the best fictional restaurants|accessdate=July 18, 2019|date=July 29, 2017|work=New York Daily News|publisher=Tribune Publishing|author=Bodner, Brett|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718035105/https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/best-fictional-restaurants-gallery-1.3358512|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Screen Rant]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanders |first1=Georgia |title=14 Fictional Restaurants We Wish We Could Eat At |url=https://screenrant.com/best-fictional-restaurant-movies-tv/ |website=Screen Rant |publisher=Valnet Inc. |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=February 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719075426/https://screenrant.com/best-fictional-restaurant-movies-tv/ |archive-date=July 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and food website ''[[The Daily Meal]]''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Menyes |first1=Carolyn |title=15 TV Restaurants We Wish Were Real Gallery |url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/best-tv-restaurants-slideshow |website=The Daily Meal |publisher=Spanfeller Media Group |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=March 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710224932/https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/best-tv-restaurants-slideshow |archive-date=July 10, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\u2014as a restaurant they wished were real. Similarly, as stated in [[Boston.com]], \"Sure, we can get crab cakes, but we wish we could try the Krusty Krab's signature sandwich, the Krabby Patties. If only we could get a suit like [[Sandy Cheeks|Sandy]]'s and journey to Bikini Bottom\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/tv/cartoon_things_we_wish_were_real?pg=7|title=Cartoon-eality: If cartoons came to life|year=2013|website=Boston.com|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners|accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> In another list published by ''The Daily Meal'', the Krusty Krab was voted number one of \"all the fictional spots currently on TV that our readers wished they could dine at\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gordon |first1=Lauren |title=Favorite TV Hangout Spots: On Air Now (Slideshow) |url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/favorite-tv-hangout-spots-air-now-slideshow/slide-10 |website=The Daily Meal |publisher=Spanfeller Media Group |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |date=August 30, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719075422/https://www.thedailymeal.com/entertain/favorite-tv-hangout-spots-air-now-slideshow/slide-10 |archive-date=July 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine listed the Krusty Krab as one of the 18 most influential fictional companies.<ref name=\"infl comp\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4351022/influential-fake-companies/|title=The 18 Most Influential Fake Companies of All Time|accessdate=June 7, 2016|date=June 2, 2016|work=Time|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602175058/http://time.com/4351022/influential-fake-companies/?xid=homepage|archivedate=June 2, 2016|first1=Alex|last1=Fitzpatrick|first2=Matt|last2=Vella|first3=Lisa|last3=Eadicicco|first4=Matt|last4=Peckham|first5=John Patrick|last5=Pullen|first6=Sarah|last6=Begley|first7=Daniel|last7=D'Addario}}</ref>\n\n===Real-life versions===\n====Imitations====\n{{external media\n|width   = 200px\n|image1  = [https://web.archive.org/web/20190718102846/http://www.yummypick.com/wp-content/uploads//2014/10/Krusty-Krab-1--dcc8b2bd731f04fd960d449177e218d8.jpg View of the exterior of Salta Burgers' real-life Krusty Krab replica in Ramallah]\n|image2  = [https://web.archive.org/web/20190718103518/http://www.yummypick.com/wp-content/uploads//2014/10/Krusty-Krab-2--fec1fe3d954306a9982abf58c2f028c7.jpg Scene inside the building] with tables, chairs, cash register booth, and other detailing similar to those of the television series.\n}}\nThe Krusty Krab has inspired several real-life establishments unaffiliated with Nickelodeon or its parent company, Viacom. In [[Monteverde|Santa Elena]], Costa Rica, a restaurant called the Krusty Krab opened in 2012 but closed a year later.<ref name=\"HeavyPalestine\">{{cite web |last1=Morgan |first1=Emily |title=Krusty Krab in Palestine: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2014/07/krusty-krab-restaurant-spongebob-squarepants-palestine-salta-burgers/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=April 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718003939/https://heavy.com/entertainment/2014/07/krusty-krab-restaurant-spongebob-squarepants-palestine-salta-burgers/ |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Ramallah]], Palestine, a company called Salta Burgers constructed a real-life Krusty Krab,<ref name=\"WPPalestine\">{{cite web |last1=McDonald |first1=Soraya Nadia |title='SpongeBob's' Krusty Krab is opening \u2014 in the West Bank |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/07/22/spongebobs-krusty-krab-is-opening-in-palestine/ |website=The Washington Post |publisher=Nash Holdings |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=July 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"THRPalestine\">{{cite news | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/photos-krusty-krab-restaurant-open-719889 | title='SpongeBob SquarePants': Real-Life Krusty Krab Restaurant to Open in Palestine | work=The Hollywood Reporter | date=July 21, 2014 | accessdate=August 12, 2014 | author=Nordyke, Kimberly | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811145501/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/photos-krusty-krab-restaurant-open-719889 | archive-date=August 11, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> which received online attention.<ref name=\"ElitePalestine\">{{cite web |last1=Anthony |first1=Robert |title=The Real-Life Krusty Krab Has Left Bikini Bottom And Is Now Open In Palestine (Photos) |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/envision/food/krusty-krab-now-open/710287 |website=Elite Daily |publisher=Bustle Digital Group |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718095341/https://www.elitedaily.com/envision/food/krusty-krab-now-open/710287 |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It opened on July{{nbsp}}24, 2014,<ref name=\"FusionPalestine\">{{cite web|title=Inside the Krusty Krab restaurant now open for business in Palestine|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vyfozQGnne0|website=Fusion TV|publisher=Univision Communications|accessdate=July 17, 2019|date=December 16, 2014|via=YouTube|format=video|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427145333/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vyfozQGnne0|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> serving seafood and its own version of the Krabby Patty;<ref name=\"HeavyPalestine\"/><ref name=\"THRPalestine\"/><ref name=\"TOIPalestine\">{{cite web |title=Spongebob-themed eatery hits Ramallah |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ramallahs-spongebob-themed-eatery/ |website=The Times of Israel |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=June 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717182227/https://www.timesofisrael.com/ramallahs-spongebob-themed-eatery/ |archive-date=July 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2017|lc=yes}}, the restaurant is still in operation.<ref name=\"HuffPalestine\">{{cite web |title=Your Favorite Cartoon Foods Are Now Available To Eat IRL |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/your-favorite-cartoon-foo_b_9533682 |website=HuffPost |publisher=Verizon Media |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=March 23, 2016}}</ref> Some commentators, like in the ''[[Houston Press]]'' noted of these foreign imitations that \"The long arm of U.S. trademark law doesn't reach across international waters. Every country has its own filing process that must be followed\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Phaedra |title=Viacom Sues Houston Firm, Says It Can't Use The Krusty Krab Name From SpongeBob SquarePants |url=https://www.houstonpress.com/restaurants/things-to-do-upcoming-food-and-drink-events-in-houston-this-week-11320757 |website=Houston Press |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=February 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716161850/https://www.houstonpress.com/restaurants/things-to-do-upcoming-food-and-drink-events-in-houston-this-week-11320757 |archive-date=July 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Moscow]], a Krusty Krab-[[theme restaurant|themed restaurant]] called The Krusty Krab Cafe opened in 2016 and also makes unofficial Krabby Patties.<ref name=\"MetroMoscow\">{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/02/22/a-real-life-version-of-the-krusty-krab-restaurant-from-spongebob-squarepants-has-just-opened-5711591/ |title=There's a new real-life version of the cafe from Spongebob Squarepants |work=Metro |date=February 22, 2016 |accessdate=May 12, 2019 |author=Hardingham-Gill, Tamara |publisher=DMG Media |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630081229/https://metro.co.uk/2016/02/22/a-real-life-version-of-the-krusty-krab-restaurant-from-spongebob-squarepants-has-just-opened-5711591/ |archive-date=June 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Davao City]], Philippines, a coffee shop opened in 2017 and sells Krabby Patty-inspired sandwiches; it was named KrustyKrub Cafe because the son of its husband-and-wife owners is a fan of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/164654|title=KrustyKrub Cafe: Business proposal turned into reality|first=Ivy C.|last=Tejano|work=SunStar|date=September 18, 2017|accessdate=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717182232/https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/164654|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Viacom sued IJR Capital Investments after learning that it had applied to trademark the Krusty Krab name at the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office|U.S. Patent and Trademark Office]] (USPTO) in December 2014.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\">{{cite web |last1=Langford |first1=Cameron |title=Judge Says Restaurant Can't Be Called 'Krusty Krab' |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-says-restaurant-cant-be-called-krusty-krab/ |publisher=Courthouse News Service |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=January 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207135014/https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-says-restaurant-cant-be-called-krusty-krab/ |archive-date=February 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The latter was planning to open two restaurants adopting the moniker in Houston and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\">{{cite web |last1=Langford |first1=Cameron |title=Fifth Circuit Rules for Viacom in 'Krusty Krab' Restaurant Case |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/fifth-circuit-rules-for-viacom-in-krusty-krab-restaurant-case/ |publisher=Courthouse News Service |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=May 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225195347/https://www.courthousenews.com/fifth-circuit-rules-for-viacom-in-krusty-krab-restaurant-case/ |archive-date=December 25, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the lawsuit, Viacom claimed that the proposed restaurants would be an infringement, even though Viacom had not filed a formal trademark for the Krusty Krab name.<ref name=\"ViceRamos\">{{cite web |last1=Sen |first1=Mayukh |title=Nickelodeon Forbids Man from Naming Restaurant 'Krusty Krab' |url=https://www.vice.com/en_asia/article/gy8qm7/nickelodeon-forbids-man-from-naming-restaurant-krusty-krab |publisher=Vice Media |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> IJR owner, Javier Ramos Jr. claimed he thought of the name, referring to \"the crust that sticks to the top of crabs when they are put in a seafood boil\".<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/> He claimed not to have heard of the Krusty Krab in ''SpongeBob SquarePants'', and that he chose it after checking Google and finding no restaurants using that name.<ref name=\"ReutersRamos\">{{cite web|title=Viacom's SpongeBob keeps rights to Krusty Krab restaurant name|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/viacom-lawsuit-spongebob/viacoms-spongebob-keeps-rights-to-krusty-krab-restaurant-name-idUSL2N1ST1QD|website=Reuters|first=Jonathan|last=Stempel|accessdate=July 18, 2019|date=May 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524093252/https://www.reuters.com/article/viacom-lawsuit-spongebob/viacoms-spongebob-keeps-rights-to-krusty-krab-restaurant-name-idUSL2N1ST1QD|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While the USPTO approved IJR's trademark application,<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\"/><ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/> a Texas federal judge ruled in January 2017 that IJR violated Viacom's rights to the ''SpongeBob'' property,<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-rules-krusty-krab-restaurant-violates-viacoms-spongebob-rights-963632|title=Judge Rules 'Krusty Krab' Restaurant Violates Viacom's 'SpongeBob' Rights|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 11, 2017|last=Gardner|first=Eriq|access-date=January 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113152713/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-rules-krusty-krab-restaurant-violates-viacoms-spongebob-rights-963632|archive-date=January 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2017/01/12/spongebob-and-krusty-krab-prevail-in-real-life-trademark-battle/|title=SpongeBob and Krusty Krab Prevail in Real-Life Trademark Battle|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=January 12, 2017|last=Gershman|first=Jacob|access-date=August 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116025214/https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2017/01/12/spongebob-and-krusty-krab-prevail-in-real-life-trademark-battle/|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> citing \"ownership of a trademark is established by use, not by registration\".<ref name=\"CNSRamos2017\"/> The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] decided in May 2018 that Viacom deserves trademark protection for the Krusty Krab, and that IJR cannot use it.<ref name=\"CNSRamos2018\"/><ref name=\"ReutersRamos\"/>\n\n====San Diego Comic-Con 2019====\n[[File:Krusty Krab exhibit (48344458757).jpg|thumb|right|Nickelodeon's Krusty Krab replica at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\nIn celebration of the 20th anniversary of ''SpongeBob'', Nickelodeon recreated the Krusty Krab building at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]].<ref name=\"AltPressSDCC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/spongebob-nickelodeon-bikini-bottom-comic-con/|title=SPONGEBOB ANNIVERSARY HONORED WITH REPLICA BIKINI BOTTOM AT COMIC-CON|author=Darus, Alex|date=July 18, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|website=Alternative Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718212356/https://www.altpress.com/news/spongebob-nickelodeon-bikini-bottom-comic-con/|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/m/star-wars-episode-ix/134769/news/77-photos-of-star-wars-avengers-the-witcher-and-more-from-the-sdcc-show-floor-comic-con-2019|title=77 Photos of Star Wars, Avengers, The Witcher and More From the SDCC Show Floor - Comic-Con 2019|author=Collura, Scott|publisher=IGN|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719025312/https://za.ign.com/m/star-wars-episode-ix/134769/news/77-photos-of-star-wars-avengers-the-witcher-and-more-from-the-sdcc-show-floor-comic-con-2019|archive-date=July 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Inside, attendees could play an interactive game in which they must complete food orders before running out of time.<ref name=\"DeadlineSDCC\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/spongebob-squarepants-san-diego-comic-con-20th-anniversary-1202634218/|title='SpongeBob SquarePants' 20th Anniversary To Pop Confetti At San Diego Comic-Con|author=D'Alessandro, Anthony|date=June 18, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630092536/https://deadline.com/2019/06/spongebob-squarepants-san-diego-comic-con-20th-anniversary-1202634218/|archive-date=June 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"SRSDCC\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/spongebob-squarepants-20th-anniversary-san-diego-comic-con-2019/amp/|title=SpongeBob Celebrating 20th Anniversary At San Diego Comic-Con 2019|author=Tyler, Adrienne|date=June 18, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019|website=Screen Rant|publisher=Valnet Inc.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719025311/https://screenrant.com/spongebob-squarepants-20th-anniversary-san-diego-comic-con-2019/amp/|archive-date=July 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was part of Nickelodeon's {{convert|1800|ft2|m2|adj=on}} booth<ref name=\"DeadlineSDCC\" /> at the event, which was dedicated to the show.<ref name=\"AltPressSDCC\" /> It featured real-life replicas of [[Mrs. Puff]]'s Boating School and the Chum Bucket, which stood {{convert|22|ft|m}} tall and allowed attendees to buy collectibles and have autographs from the show's [[List of SpongeBob SquarePants cast members|cast members]].<ref name=\"DeadlineSDCC\"/><ref name=\"SRSDCC\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that the Bikini Bottom setup \"drew hundreds of nostalgic fans\" on the first day of the convention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-07-19/la-et-comic-con-sponge-bob-stephen-hillenburg|title=\u2018SpongeBob\u2019 actors get tearful remembering creator Stephen Hillenburg at Comic-Con|author=Schoellkopf, Christina|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=July 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725195830/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-07-19/la-et-comic-con-sponge-bob-stephen-hillenburg|archive-date=July 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Adweek]]'' named it among its ten \"Favorite TV-Themed Activations at Comic-Con 2019\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/our-10-favorite-tv-themed-activations-at-comic-con-2019/|title=Our 10 Favorite TV-Themed Activations at Comic-Con 2019|work=Adweek|publisher=Beringer Capital|author=Jerde, Sara|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=July 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726071006/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/our-10-favorite-tv-themed-activations-at-comic-con-2019/|archive-date=July 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Beck84\">{{harvnb|Beck|2013|page=84}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aPRymAEACAAJ|title=The SpongeBob SquarePants Experience: A Deep Dive Into the World of Bikini Bottom|publisher=Insight Editions|last=Beck|first=Jerry|author-link=Jerry Beck|date=2013|isbn=978-1-60887-184-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|Nickelodeon}}\n\n*{{Facebook|TheKrustyKrabOfficial}}\n\n{{SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional restaurants]]\n[[Category:SpongeBob SquarePants]]\n", "name_user": "RFalls", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krusty_Krab"}
{"title_page": "Isiah Whitlock Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Isiah Whitlock Jr.\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1954|9|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]], [[Indiana]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Southwest Minnesota State University]]\n| occupation         = [[Actor]]\n| other_names        = \n| years_active       = 1981\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Isiah Whitlock Jr.''' (born September 13, 1954) is an American actor.\n\n==Early life==\nWhitlock was born in [[South Bend, Indiana]]. He attended college at [[Southwest Minnesota State University]] in [[Marshall, Minnesota]], where he enrolled earned a [[college football|football]] [[Athletic scholarship|scholarship]] and studied theater. Injuries led him to stop playing football and focus on acting.<ref name=WhitlockScholarship/> After graduating in 1976, he moved to [[San Francisco]] and joined the [[American Conservatory Theater]].<ref name=MI021111>Karin Elton, [http://www.marshallindependent.com/page/content.detail/id/526305/A-perfect-fit.html A perfect fit], ''Marshall Independent'', February 11, 2011, accessed June 14, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhitlock is best known for his role on the [[HBO]] television series ''[[The Wire (TV series)|The Wire]]'' as corrupt state senator [[Clay Davis]]. He has also appeared in the [[Spike Lee]] films ''[[She Hate Me]]'', ''[[25th Hour]]'', ''[[Red Hook Summer]]'', ''[[Chi-Raq]]'' and ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''. In those projects, Whitlock established a [[catchphrase]] from his character's distinct pronunciation of the word \"shit\" (\"sheeeeeeeee-it\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/tv_club/features/2008/the_wire_final_season/week_10_how_sheeeit_started.html|title=The Wire Final Season: Week 10: How Sheee-it Started|publisher=[[Slate.com]]|author=Swansburg, John|date=March 12, 2008|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref> Whitlock also made appearances on ''[[Chappelle's Show]]'' and has made several appearances as various characters on ''[[Law & Order]]''. He appeared as Eugene, a supporting role, in the 2003 film ''[[Pieces of April]]''. He had a bit part in ''[[Goodfellas]]'' as a doctor who gives [[Henry Hill]] Valium while attending to his brother. He also made an appearance in the film ''[[1408 (film)|1408]]'', as the [[engineer]] of the Dolphin Hotel, as well as appearing in promotional spots for the [[Wii]] video game ''[[Punch-Out!! (Wii)|Punch-Out!!]]'' portraying the character [[Doc Louis]]. In 2007, he played Ethan Banks in ''[[Enchanted (2007 film)|Enchanted]]''.\n\nWhitlock played an insurance agent named Ronald Wilkes in the 2011 film ''[[Cedar Rapids (film)|Cedar Rapids]]''. Wilkes is a self-described fan of ''The Wire'' and does an impersonation of character [[Omar Little]]. Whitlock has said that the references to the series were written in before he became involved in ''Cedar Rapids''.<ref name=thewire>{{Citation \n  | last = Rich\n  | first = Katey\n  | title = Interview: The Wire's Isiah Whitlock Jr. Plays Against Type In Cedar Rapids\n  | pages = \n  | newspaper = CinemaBlend.com\n  | location = \n  | date = February 10, 2011\n  | url =http://www.cinemablend.com/new/interview-the-wire-s-isiah-whitlock-jr-plays-against-type-in-cedar-rapids-23100.html\n  | accessdate =February 21, 2011 }}</ref> Whitlock filmed a separate promotion for the film, where Wilkes is seen in an insurance office reading lines from ''The Wire''.<ref name=YouTubeWilkes>{{YouTube|AHPZ7QWPI8U|CEDAR RAPIDS: Ronald vs. Omar from the Wire}}, Fox Searchlight official channel via YouTube.com, February 7, 2011.</ref> He currently recurs on the [[Home Box Office|HBO]] comedy series ''[[Veep (TV series)|Veep]]'' as General George Maddox. Whitlock has also made appearances on ''[[The Good Wife]]'', ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]'', ''[[Gotham (TV series)|Gotham]]'', ''[[The Carmichael Show]]'', and ''[[Elementary (TV series)|Elementary]]''. He recently appeared as the sheriff in the 2016 remake of the [[Pete's Dragon (1977 film)|1977 film]] of ''[[Pete's Dragon (2016 film)|Pete's Dragon]]''.\n\nSMSU now offers the Isiah Whitlock Jr. Endowed Scholarship.<ref name=WhitlockScholarship>[http://www.smsufoundation.org/s/1158/interior.aspx?sid=1158&pgid=366&gid=1&cid=955&ecid=955&post_id=0 Isiah Whitlock Jr. Endowed Scholarship], Southwest Minnesota State University Foundation, accessed June 14, 2012.</ref> He was SMSU's commencement speaker in 1999 and guest artist for the school's celebration of [[Black History Month]] in 2007.<ref name=MI021111/>\n\nCapitalizing on his catch phrase \"[[Shit|Sheeeeeeeee-it]]\" and his public notoriety, Whitlock launched a successful [[Kickstarter]] Talking [[Bobblehead]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1556507886/isiah-whitlock-jr-talking-bobblehead/video_share|title=Isiah Whitlock, Jr. Talking Bobblehead|website=Kickstarter|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-25}}</ref> The campaign has raised over $100,000 from 1,828 backers.\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Gremlins 2: The New Batch]]''\n|Fireman\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Goodfellas]]''\n|Doctor\n|\n|-1992+\n''.Candyman\nPolice line-up participant\n\n|1996\n|[[Eddie (film)|''Eddie'']]\n|Rick\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Everyone Says I Love You]]''\n|Cop\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[The Spanish Prisoner]]''\n|Trooper\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[A Fish in the Bathtub]]''\n|Rudy\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''Harlem Aria''\n|Manny\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Jump Tomorrow]]''\n|George's Uncle\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''Driving Fish''\n|Mason\n|Short\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[25th Hour]]''\n|Agent Flood\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Pieces of April]]''\n|Eugene\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''Bought & Sold''\n|Mr. Stubbs\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[She Hate Me]]''\n|Agent Amos Flood\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''Honey Trap''\n|The Detective\n|Short\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Duane Hopwood]]''\n|William\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''Stealing Martin Lane''\n|Harold \"Chopper\" Jones\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Kettle of Fish (film)|Kettle of Fish]]''\n|Freddie\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|[[Beautiful Ohio (film)|''Beautiful Ohio'']]\n|Mr. Lebreaux\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''A Nick in Time''\n|Old Bob Delagard\n|Short\n|-\n|2007\n|[[1408 (film)|''1408'']]\n|Hotel Engineer\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''The Man in My House''\n|T.J.\n|Short\n|-\n|2007\n|[[Enchanted (film)|''Enchanted'']]\n|Ethan Banks\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|[[Choke (film)|''Choke'']]\n|Detective Palmer\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Cadillac Records]]''\n|Mississippi DJ\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''The Thing We Know''\n|Keith\n|Short\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Brooklyn's Finest]]''\n|Investigator #3\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[I Hate Valentine's Day]]''\n|Drummer\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''Under New Management''\n|Rev. A.L. Blunton\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''Speed Grieving''\n|Dr. Holder\n|Short\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Twelve (2010 film)|''Twelve'']]\n|Detective Dummont\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Main Street (2010 film)|''Main Street'']]\n|Mayor\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Gun Hill Road (film)|''Gun Hill Road'']]\n|Officer Thompson\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Cedar Rapids (film)|''Cedar Rapids'']]\n|Ronald Wilkes\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Detachment (film)|''Detachment'']]\n|Mr. Mathias\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Red Hook Summer]]''\n|Detective Flood\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Why Stop Now (film)|''Why Stop Now?'']]\n|Black\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Thanks for Sharing]]''\n|Charles\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Not Fade Away (film)|''Not Fade Away'']]\n|Landers\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''Newlyweeds''\n|Philly\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Europa Report]]''\n|Dr. Tarik Pamuk\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''Home''\n|Samuel\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''Jerome's Bouquet''\n|Jack\n|Short\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Angriest Man in Brooklyn]]''\n|Yates\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[23 Blast]]''\n|Dr. Connelly\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Chi-Raq]]''\n|Bacchos\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Pete's Dragon (2016 film)|''Pete's Dragon'']]\n|Sheriff Gene Dentler \n|\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Person to Person (film)|''Person to Person'']]\n|Buster\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[CHiPs (film)|CHiPs]]''\n|Peterson\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Cars 3]]''\n|River Scott\n|Voice role\n|-\n|2017\n|''Sloan Hearts Neckface''\n|Lester\n|Short film\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''\n|Mr. Turrentine\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[All Square]]''\n|Scotty\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Old Man & the Gun]]''\n|Detective Gene Dentler\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Corporate Animals]]''\n|Derek\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''Lost Holiday''\n|Matthews\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Lying and Stealing]]''\n|Lyman Wilkers\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''Run with the Hunted''\n|Lester\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''Seneca''\n|Michael\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''The Lost Husband''\n|Russ McAllen\n|\n|-\n|TBA\n|''[[Da 5 Bloods]]''\n|\n|Post-production\n|-\n|TBA\n|''[[I Care a Lot]]''\n|\n|Post-production\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1981\n|''A Christmas Carol''\n|Second Charitable Gentleman/Party Guest\n|Television movie\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Cagney & Lacey]]''\n|Unknown\n|Episode: \"The City is Burning\"\n|-\n|1989\n|''Ocean''\n|The Moose\n|Miniseries; 6 episodes\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Alex Haley's Queen|Queen]]''\n|Preacher\n|Miniseries; 1 episode\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Anthony White\n|Episode: \"Guardian\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Simon Brooks\n|Episode: \"Trophy\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Fred Oates\n|Episode: \"Slave\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[New York Undercover]]''\n|Chief Hardin\n|Episode: \"Bad Blood\"\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Liberty!|Liberty! The American Revolution]]''\n|Luke (Slave)\n|Miniseries; 6 episodes\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Third Watch]]''\n|Reggie Simmons\n|Episode: \"Impulse\"\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Fred Oakes\n|Episode: \"Loco Parentis\"\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n|Robbery Division Captain\n|Episode: \"Limitations\"\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Capt. Navarro\n|Episode: \"Standoff\"\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Wonderland (U.S. TV series)|Wonderland]]''\n|Reviewer\n|